n Missile Crisis took place in the age of Twitter, with unvetted information swirling around? What if an adversary announced that malware had compromised nuclear systems, clouding the confidence of nuclear decision-makers? Cyber Threats and Nuclear Weapons, the first book to consider cyber risks across the entire nuclear enterprise, concludes with crucial advice on how government can manage the tensions between new nuclear capabilities and increasing cyber risk. This is an invaluable handbook for those ready to confront the unique challenges of cyber nuclear risk.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aCommand and control systemsxSecurity measureszUnited States. 0aComputer securityzUnited States. 0aCyberspace operations (Military science)zUnited States. 0aNuclear weaponsxSecurity measureszUnited States. 0aNuclear weaponszUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh  aCyber-nuclear connection.  aand communications.  acomplexity-security tradeoff.  acontrol.  aconventional-nuclear integration.  acyber risk.  ainadvertent escalation.  anuclear command.  anuclear delivery systems.  anuclear weapons.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073914540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363040640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503630406423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503630406/original  a978-3-11-073914-5  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles